FACILITATOR NOTES & TEACHING TIPS

Common Student Mistakes to Watch For:

  1. Over-apologizing: Students from academic backgrounds often write âIâm extremely sorryâ three times. Coach them: apologize once, then focus on the solution.

  2. Burying the lead: They write 3 paragraphs of context before stating what they need. Redirect: âStart with the ask.â

  3. Vague language: âSoon,â âASAP,â âsome issues.â Push for specifics: âBy when exactly?â âWhat issues specifically?â

  4. Fear of being direct: Cultural tendency to soften everything. Teach: âDirect â  rude. Direct = respectful of time.â

Time Management:

  • If opening exercise runs long (students enjoying debate), cut Element 5 discussion short
  • If students struggle with writing challenge, extend to 20 minutes and reduce pair feedback to 5 minutes
  • Always protect the final 10 minutes for homework assignment

Differentiation:

  • Advanced students: Challenge them to write the client email in under 100 words without losing key information
  • Struggling students: Give them a template structure: âOpening (problem) â Explanation (brief) â Solution (specific) â Next steps (clear)â

Assessment Signals:
